http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/Amma-marriage-halls-in-11-places-across-TN/article14460651.ece

 Announcing the launch of Amma marriage halls catering to the needs of the poor, Chief Minister Jayalalithaa on Saturday announced mega housing projects worth over Rs. 1,500 crore targetting the economically weaker sections of society. In a statement, Ms. Jayalalithaa said 11 Amma marriage halls, including six in Chennai, will come up at a cost of Rs. 83 crore. In Chennai, the halls will be constructed at Tondiarpet, Velachery, Ayapakkam, Paruthipattu, Periyar Nagar and Koratur. The rest will come up in Madurai (Anna Nagar), Tirunelveli (Ambasamudram), Salem city, Tiruvallur (Kodungaiyur) and Tirupur (Udumalpet). The halls will be set up for the poor who cannot afford to pay huge rent. The halls will have air-conditioned rooms for the bride and groom, make-up room, guest rooms and all the required facilities at low rent, she said. Reservation for the halls will be done online, she added. Housing projects In the past five years, the Tamil Nadu Slum Clearance Board has built 59,023 houses and work on 10,537 houses was under way. This year, Ms. Jayalalithaa said she had ordered the TNSCB to construct 50,000 houses at a cost of Rs. 1,800 crore.The government will provide a subsidy of Rs. 945 crore covering 45,000 houses for the beneficiaries planning in situ construction. In Sholinganallur, the Tamil Nadu Housing Board (TNHB) is constructing 1,500 apartments. In continuity, this year 2,000 more flats will be built at a cost of Rs. 600 crore. Houses for low-income group measuring 645 sq.ft will be available below Rs. 20 lakh and flats measuring 807 sq.ft will be priced below Rs. 30 lakh. Repairing govt. quartersThe government quarters in Dindigul, Madurai, Pudukottai, Tiruchi, Erode and Hosure were in a damaged condition. About Rs. 400 crore will be spent on demolishing these structures and build new houses and to build 1,266 more houses for sale, the Chief Minister said. She also announced waiver of interest for 23,600 persons allotted houses, flats or plots by the TNHB, according to the release.